Follow-up devices are increasingly being asked by parents who want to monitor their children.
The fear of their child is increasing, leading more and more people to think about monitoring them through a GPS.
The system, set up at the beginning to search for cars, can also be used to track the movement of people and help in some cases, such as the one of the little Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is now as large as a box of lamps but will soon be the size of a watch.
The case of little Anicka has given birth to a large number of people and they have begun to look for ways to better protect their children.
Even if the price is to disturb their privacy.
"We are trying to tell everyone that this is not spying but only another way to reduce the likelihood that there is another tragedy," says Petr Pilin of the company Macro Weil, who is one of the suppliers of tracking devices on the Czech market.
"I assume there may be cases of misuse of such devices, such as putting them in the bag of a person who is not aware, but I have not yet met such cases."
"Most people are customers who actually buy the product for security reasons," adds Pilin.
According to him, children should always know what purposes "the box" is used and how to use it in case of emergency.
Children's psychologist Dana Bockova points out that if the child doesn't want to wear such a thing on him, he will get rid of it.
'And even the smallest ones can show great creativity when it comes to getting rid of something explicitly when they don't want to be under control.'
"The mobile phones, which can cut themselves like these tracking devices, have already brought the parents to long expectations," Bockova says.
According to her, the fact that this type of device can help in the event of aggression is very controversial.
"If this is a prepared kidnapping, the author will do everything to ensure that the child does not have an electronic device that can locate it."
"At present, it's the phone."
"As soon as the tracking devices develop, they (criminals) will also seek them because the sale will be supported by an advertising campaign."
"In such cases, criminals will always be in advance on the police," says the psychologist.
It also admits that such devices can help in an attack not prepared by a pedophile.
According to Robert Cech of the RC Monitoring company, which offers tracking services for both cars and people, claims that having this type of device can help, even if it is destroyed in the event of an aggression.
"The apparatus may be measured in such a way that it is in regular emission after a specified period".
"In the event that the device is destroyed, it remains the last position of the person concerned."
'The most expensive devices also have a terminal meter that immediately signals the position of the person who has slipped and is in a position that is lengthened without moving,' says Cech.
According to him, smartphones that are intelligent, which are equipped with a navigation system, can offer a comparable service after having formatted it with a special prologial.
The problem with the current tracking systems is that it is a device similar to that which is carried in relation to the size of a lamp box or to the smallest telephone devices.
We can always lose them.
According to Pilina of Macro Weil, this is why tests are being carried out now to make devices similar to common digital watches.
"This will have the advantage that any attacker will not be able to recognize the tracking device."
"Or he'll realize after a while, which will give the police a little more time," he adds.
Whether the tracking device is developed in the form of a bracelet or pendant, it will always use the same technology as to track cars.
This is a combination of a GPS positioning system (which is commonly used in self-navigation) and a function of a mobile phone that alerts the current position of a vehicle.
