Men who have the index longer than the index are exposed to less risk of having prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday by the British magazine Cancer.
This may depend on the level of hormone male testosterone.
"Our conclusions show that the relative length of the finger is a simple test of the risk of prostate cancer, especially for men 60 years ago," said the co-author of the Ros Eeles study, professor at the University of Warwick for cancer research.
The finger could thus help determine which men should submit to the prostate cancer test, including by combining with the genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health history, Eeles added.
During the period 1994-2009, she followed with her colleagues in Great Britain more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had the index of the right hand shorter than the yearbook.
For them as for 19 percent of those who had their fingers of the same length, the same probability of prostate cancer was found.
However, in the case of those with a longer index than the index, the risk index fell to 33 per cent, for men before 60 years the risk reduction reached 87 per cent.
The length report of the two fingers mentioned - formed during the prenatal period - indicates, among other things, different levels of sexual hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
Unless testosterone corresponds to a longer index.
Previous research has shown that it is just testosterone that helps develop prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, said to CTK that he is aware of this study, but he does not seem to think that the relationship between the length of fingers and cancer is "completely demonstrated".
