Support for democracy in Latin America continues to increase, as did the support for private enterprise.
Crime has become more worrying than unemployment.
And Brazil is seen as more influential than the United States in much of the region.
These are some of the conclusions of the last Latinobarometer survey taken in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
As the survey has been conducted on a regular basis since 1995, it has followed changes in attitudes in the region.
Two related elements are the results of this year's survey, carried out in September and early October.
The first is the fairly sunny mood of Latin America.
The second is the growing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased significantly in several countries around the South American Pacific (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has reached an average of 6% per year since 2002, support for democracy has increased from at least 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It has also increased in Mexico, where the economy has recovered after a strong decline in production last year.
However, only about half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries in the region, are convinced Democrats, reducing the regional average (see Table 2).
