A microbe tolerating arsenic raises the possibility of new types of life on Earth, or elsewhere.
The discovery of a foreign bacteria, which can use arsenic as one of its nutrients, expands the field to find new forms of life on Earth and perhaps beyond.
Although researchers have discovered the unusual bacteria here on Earth, they say it shows that life has opportunities beyond the major elements that have been considered essential.
"This organism has a dual capacity."
"It can develop with either phosphorus or arsenic."
"That's why she's very special, even though she's far from being a really "foreign" life form," commented Paul Davies C. W. of the University of Arizona, co-author of the report appearing in the online edition of Thursday's journal Science.
Six major elements have long been considered essential for life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulphur.
But researchers have discovered that the bacteria, discovered in Lake Mono, California, are able to continue to develop after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
"We wonder what is still possible," said Ariel Anbar D. of the University of Arizona, co-author of the report.
The discovery is important in the search for life beyond Earth because researchers must be able to recognize life, to know what life looks like, says Anbar.
The study focuses on a microbe found on Earth.
However, the announcement of a press conference to discuss it, which did not disclose the details of the bottle, generated widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could reveal the discovery of an extraterrestrial life.
That wasn't the case.
The discovery "shows that, in other planetary environments, organisms could be able to use other elements to act on biochemistry and that all "standard" elements, which we consider absolutely necessary for life, could not be fixed," commented Charles Cockell, professor of planetary and space science research at the Institute of Open University, Milton Keynes, United Kingdom.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
"This work is new because it shows the substitution of one element to another in basic biochemistry and the biochemical structure," Cockell added.
It wasn't a lucky discovery.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of the NASA Institute of Astrology, who conducted the study, chose Lake Mono because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar; thus, it has speculated that one microbe exposed to both substances could be able to replace one another.
"Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is really similar to that of phosphorus."
"As a result, organisms have difficulty distinguishing these elements separately."
"But arsenic is different enough so it doesn't work exactly like phosphorus; it penetrates inside and somehow rubbers the work of our biochemical machine," Anbar explained.
The researchers collected the known bacteria called GFAJ-1 and exposed it to increasing concentrations of arsenic to which it could adapt and grow.
The microbe grows better with phosphorus but the fact that it can live with arsenic at the site raises the possibility that a life form using arsenic can naturally occur, either on Earth or on another planet or the moon where arsenic is more frequent.
Jamie S. Foster, associate professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said that the idea that arsenic could be replaced by phosphorus was not new; but nothing has ever shown that this could work.
Arsenic was more frequent at the beginning of the existence of the Earth, she said; thus, the researchers issued the hypothesis that the first forms of life could have used it.
This suggests that there may be other ways to form life, not only the way life on Earth was formed at the beginning," said Foster, who was not part of the Wolfe-Simon research team.
The research was funded by NASA, the Ministry of Energy and the National Institute of Health.
