A Global Plan to Renovate Light
The United Nations proposed yesterday in Cancún a plan for the renovation of domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries with a view to achieving a greenhouse gas reduction (GGE) corresponding to almost a third of the additional reduction needed to stabilise the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is in the crowd of major concrete projects that the United Nations hopes to adopt in Cancún to compensate for the absence of binding commitments to reduce by industrialized countries.
According to yesterday's plan, if the incandescent ampoules that are still monopolizing from 50 to 70% of the market were replaced by fluocompact ampoules or, better, by electroluminescent diodes (DEL or "LED") ampoules, the essential of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of GES emitted on the planet would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is the equivalent of 70% of the emissions of the planetary car park.
In Copenhagen, last year, large emitters such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans that should bring GES global emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will have to be removed from this balance sheet another 5 Gt in order to stabilise by 2020 the rise of the climate to 2 degrees centigrade in order to avoid it becoming out of control.
In the incandescent ampoules, 95% of the energy is dissipated in the form of heat and the rest, or 5%, is produced by light.
With fluocompact ampoules, energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with new LED ampoules, this need for energy is reduced twice again.
Fluocompact ampoules last from 6000 to 10,000 hours on average.
New LED ampoules, such as those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week - this company also participated in the study of the United Nations - have a living hope of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent ampoule, which gives an idea of the economy with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
All these new ampoules can also work with rheostats in addition to producing very little heat.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several specialists have posted reservations to the place of fluocompact ampoules as they contain mercury and need to be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless manufacturers put in place signs.
But, says the report, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the fluocompact ampoule, but the coal thermal power plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce spent electricity in incandescent ampoules.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tonnes of mercury per year.
The report details the gains that each country would make through this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would thus save one billion dollars a year in electricity purchases and eight million tons of CO2, or the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants whose construction would cost 2.5 billion.
